rji argues that it was a product of collective intelligence, depending on peasant women and artisans--unrecognized heirs to Roman traditions of engineering--who came to labor on the waterway in collaboration with military and academic supervisors. Ironically, while Louis XIV and his treasury minister Jean-Baptiste Colbert used propaganda to present France as a new Rome, the Canal du Midi was being constructed with unrecognized classical methods. Still, the result was politically potent. As Mukerji shows, the project took land and power from local nobles, using water itself as a silent agent of the state to disrupt traditions of local life that had served regional elites.Impossible Engineering opens a surprising window into the world of seventeenth-century France and illuminates a singular work of engineering undertaken to empower the state through technical conquest of nature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aTechnology & Engineering / History.2bisacsh  aAppointee.  aBenedict Anderson.  aBernard Palissy.  aBook.  aBountiful Harvest.  aBruno Latour.  aC. Wright Mills.  aCalculation.  aCambridge University Press.  aCanal du Midi.  aCarcassonne.  aCardinal Mazarin.  aChartism.  aChauvinism.  aCivil engineer.  aCivil engineering.  aClassical tradition.  aColonialism.  aContentious politics.  aCourtesy.  aDe re metallica.  aDiscipline and Punish.  aDivine right of kings.  aDrug court.  aEminent domain.  aEngineer.  aEngineering design process.  aEngineering.  aExperiential knowledge.  aFernand Braudel.  aFor the Glory.  aFratricide.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aGod's Grace.  aGovernance.  aGovernmentality.  aHandbook.  aHomeschooling.  aHuguenot.  aHydraulic engineering.  aImmanuel Wallerstein.  aInception.  aIntendant.  aJean Bodin.  aLabo